📌 Future of Blockchain

There is an awareness of the problems that it presents.

If projects are able to successfully solve the trilemma, we could be looking at new levels of blockchain adoption

🔸 Consensus Protocol Improvement

Although PoW is secure, it can be slow.

That’s why many blockchain networks favor the Proof-of-Stake (PoS) consensus mechanism.

🔸 Sidechains

A sidechain is a blockchain-adjacent transactional chain used for large batch transactions

Sidechains use an independent consensus mechanism to that of the original chain, which can be optimized for speed and scalability.

🔸 Nested Blockchains

A nested blockchain is a decentralized network infrastructure that uses the primary blockchain to specify network parameters while executions are carried out on a web of secondary chains.

📌 Searching for a solution

🔸 Ethereum 2.0: Sharding and Rollups

Sharding has become a popular solution to scale projects. Basically, when a network “shards”, it breaks the transactions up into easier sets of data that can be processed by the network quicker.

📌 Why do blockchains need to scale?

If blockchain technology is going to reach any sort of mass adoption, scalability is critical.

If a network can’t scale, it just won’t be able to compete with traditional platforms in transaction speed, and throughput.

📌 Trade-Off

Blockchains are often forced to make trade-offs that prevent them from achieving all the 3 aspects

While developers believe that the blockchain data structure itself has inherent limitations, many architects, believe that it’s possible to hit all three targets

📌 What is the blockchain trilemma?

The Blockchain Trilemma, coined by @VitalikButerin, discusses the difficulties that developers confront when establishing a blockchain that is scalable, decentralized, and safe without compromising on any aspect.

📌 The 3 pillars of blockchain and cryptocurrency

🔸 Decentralization
A system that does not rely on a central point of control

🔸 Scalability
Ability to handle an increasing amount of transactions

🔸 Security
 Ability to operate as expected, defend itself from attacks & bugs

📌 Participation

🔸 Centralization
The central authority controls who all can participate

🔹 Decentralization 
Anyone can participate, there are no gatekeepers as such

📌 Censorship

🔸 Centralization
The central authority can censor data as they wish

🔹 Decentralization 
In decentralized servers, information can propagate in different ways

📌 Point of failure

🔸 Centralization
There is a single point of failure

🔹 Decentralization 
There is no single point of failure, the network would be still functional if one node is down

📌 Conflicting data

🔸 Centralization
In case of conflicting data, the central authority is the ultimate source of truth(easier method of resolution)

🔹 Decentralization 
A complex protocol is often needed to resolve the conflicting data

📌 Performance

🔸 Centralization
Centralized servers perform better and have better throughput. They are also easier to implement

🔹 Decentralization 
Decentralized servers usually have lower throughput. They are complex to implement

📌Basics

🔸 Centralization
- All the users are connected to a central authority
- The data of all the users are stored in a central server

🔹 Decentralization 
- Users may have been connected to the edges
- Transfer of info may take a long time to reach from one edge to another https://t.co/Kd6Z9Rgc4j

🔸As ETH is getting more congested, higher bandwidth is required to validate a single transaction 

🔸SOL solves this problem using Turbine Protocol, breaking each transaction block into smaller packets and transmitting them

📌 Languages used

🔸ETH has its own language Solidity with is built to be compatible with EVM(Ethereum Virtual Machine)

🔸SOL is based on Rust which has a variety of uses cases

📌 Scalability 

🔸ETH in the current condition can handle around 15 transactions per second and is hence willing to switch to L2 solutions such as Polygon

🔸SOL, which is based on rust can handle up to 50K transactions per second.
That's pretty damn impressive, isn't it!

🔸Solana uses PoH, which is similar to PoS but with an extra attribute of the timestamp

The timestamp is the time passed between two cryptographic events

📌Consensus Mechanism

🔸Each blockchain has a consensus mechanism for millions of miners to participate in staking.

🔸Etheruem currently uses PoW(Proof of Work) but ETH 2.0 would be shifting to PoS(Proof of Stake) to become more eco friendly

useMemo is used to memoize costly functions so they don't have to be called every time they're rendered.

Whereas useCallback is used to improve the rendering behaviour of your React function components. https://t.co/THxuxbdDkH

useMemo

This hook is similar to the useCallback hook, but here a memoized value is returned rather than the entire function.

useMemo also has a dependency array and is called once the state in the dependency array is updated.
This will help prevent unnecessary renders and optimize the child components https://t.co/NwzYRH9k1z

useCallback

What to do when a function is being called again and again without any need. You use the useCallback hook

useCallback function will return a memoized version that of a callback function that only changes when you changed the dependency array.

But unlike useState, a change in the value of useRef doesn't cause the DOM to render.

The useRef is completely separate from the render cycle https://t.co/z0gMq9xQZy

useRef

This React Hook is used to create reference variables.

The values stored in useRef are also preserved between different renders, similar to useState.

If an empty array is provided, then the useEffect is only called once, when the DOM is mounted and is never called again.

If state variables are passed in the dependency array then useEffect is called when the state variables are updated. https://t.co/8QPptPp7G6

The array present at the end of the useEffect function is called the dependency array.

This dependency array defines how the useEffect would be used.

If no dependency array is provided then it will be called every time the DOM is updated.

useEffect

Using this hook, you tell React to do something after rendering the DOM. 

React remembers the function you passed and would call that function after performing the DOM updates. https://t.co/IBAejmgL26

The first is the name of the state variable that is declared and the second is the function that is called to update the state variable.

PS- State variable is able to hold any and all types of datatypes. https://t.co/Xwxe3p0yu8

useState

This hook as the name suggests is used to declare a state variable. This helps preserve values between function calls.

Whenever a state variable is changed it causes the DOM to re-render.
